    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1884-03-18T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1884-03-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="96" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d96">
                <head>No. 96.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Frelinghuysen</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Morton</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1884-03-18">
                            <hi rend="italic">March</hi> 18,
                            1884</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 474]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to your dispatch No. 494, of
                        the 5th ultimo, in which you make a full statement of the facts relating to
                        the case of Alfred P. Jacob, I have to say that the previous instruction was
                        based on the absence of any report from the legation in the premises and the
                        assumption that Mr. Jacob had voluntarily submitted to serve in the army
                        without recourse to diplomatic protection. His case now, as it stands, is
                        peculiar. By our laws he is an American citizen, his status as such dating
                        from his father’s naturalization.</p>
                <p>By French law he is a recognized citizen through service in the army, which
                        only a citizen can perform. That obligation to do military duty (whether
                        rightly due or not) having been extinguished, no precise issue remains on
                        which the status of Mr. Jacob could be carried before a court. To make the
                        issue, the only available way would seem to be to present the case and ask
                        that his name be stricken off. With this explanation you may make the
                        request contemplated in our No. 436.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>FRED’K T. FRELINGHUYSEN.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
